John Edward: Language skills are essential to the world’s citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with excellent new exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries.
If you look at the excellent exam results this year, you can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, show that 72% of students obtained the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did the 72% of students who studied German, the 69% of students who studied French and the 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and youth in the future.
Languages as subjects are now organized as are science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more job openings requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this sustainable skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of their competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them did not have enough fluency in a foreign language to have a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, especially those of emerging economies, children will benefit from better chances of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialized staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is clear that at present, in a global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the country's future, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
