North Korea says that disarmament can under no circumstances be achieved unilaterally without trust.
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining the sanctions heightened his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under the circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the world body, Ri Yong Ho said that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
In the absence of trust in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, it is excluded that we will be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While reiterating North Korea's well-known reproaches about Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps gradually, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work toward a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused requests to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and increases pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the "declaration of the end of the war".
“Those who think these sanctions can make us use them don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our distrust.”
Ri made no comment about the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party involved in the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a deadlock.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened last year before the United Nations to "totally destroy" North Korea, did not suffocate this year's praise for the courage with which Kim has applied disarmament measures, but added that much remains to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the United Nations Security Council last Thursday that “the implementation of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made but, in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University introduced a new course that allows all undergraduates to get more sleep and fights the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
A professor has noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student approached me and said, "Why do I get told that only in the last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
First delivered this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know this won’t instantly change student behavior.
However, in our view, they have a right to know this information – in the same way that you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in “sleeping a night out” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said — even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and prompted him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar degree program before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
