Germany's new warship still postponed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War warships, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman, the commissioning of the “Rheinland-Pfalz”, the flagship of the brand new frigate ships of Baden-Württemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the worrying problems that occurred after delivery have jeopardized the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technologies, such as a reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside of the home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that the avant-garde warships – which should allow Germany to project its force overseas – will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed frigate F125 made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to Hamburg’s Blohm & Voss shipyard.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of “software and hardware defects” that made the warship useless in case of deployment on combat missions.
The software defects were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which decreases its efficiency and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as much as the similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond computer system failures, the price of the project as a whole - including crew training - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars), compared to 2.2 billion initially.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval strength is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence commission of the German parliament, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is in fact “out of ships able to deploy”.
The official stated that the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old vessels were decommissioned but no replacement vessels were designated.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates were able to join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research from a field in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats and long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat cries as well as the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perches and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as pet cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight path.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of bats in Scotland at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Domain manager David Thompson says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave, we have a great place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of checking the presence of bats before proceeding with the maintenance of the properties, because unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest can cause the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations at the moment.”
