Red Tide Info Point: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - fearing declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from north of Pinellas to south of Lee counties.
Islets are found about 10 miles (16 km) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer locations than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, high concentrations in Charlotte County, and low concentrations in the bottom of the county.
Respiratory irritation persists in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
